Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 1:34:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=68>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Question for the mighty zaphod</span><hr size=1> Back again!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I have been doing a little tinkering with acceleration profiles for the Liberty Ship and have stumbled upon a serendipitous feature of having a low fraction of the launcher mass used as fuel on the trip up to orbit: The Liberty Ship will have a very gentle ride.<br>
<br>
Picking numbers out of the air, if the Liberty Ship has to thrust for 11 minutes to achieve orbital insertion, at a mass flow of 1245 kilograms per second, then it will consume 821,700 kilograms on the trip.  Or, 1,812,000 pounds or so.<br>
<br>
So, from a launch weight of 6,000,000 pounds, we reduce our crafts weight/mass to 4,188,000 pounds at orbital insertion.<br>
<br>
Assuming we keep our thrust levels constant at 8,400,000 pounds for the entire trip, that means we are accelerating at 1.4 g's at liftoff and a still-mild 2 g's at MECO.  This is in a trip with no staging stresses, either, and given the sturdiness we can build into the Liberty Ship's structure, we can simply plow through Max-Q without any fancy throttling crap needed.<br>
<br>
This completely fits into the &quot;big but relaxed&quot; and &quot;KISS&quot; strategy I am trying to follow here.  You light up the Liberty Ship, set the hydrogen flows and vortexes at their flight conditions, and don't mess with it again until you hit your orbital window, just watch it like a hawk to be sure nothing gets away from you.<br>
<br>
I like simple.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As a note:  Years ago I had a copy of the formula used to calculate the flight condition of a booster.  You simply plugged in such things as drag, air resistance, Isp, angle of attack, thrusts, and weights for given times and it would tell you the delta v you generated for the timeframe.  I have since lost it when I gave up on chemical HLV's and now wish I could find it again.  If anyone has a copy of such a thing, I would appreciate a link to it, or a cut and paste.  Otherwise, I fear another trip to the Librabry of Congress becomes a neccesity rather than a luxury.  &lt;sigh&gt;<br>
<br>
Now, to questions: <br>
<br>
nebobgrenville: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Sorry if I sounded like a pest, it was your comments that no one was nitpicking your design that made me ask the same question more then once. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, not to worry, I was joking.  I thought the smiley face would indicate that.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   And thanks for the questions, you've had some good ones!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Increasing the volume of the reaction chamber also reduces the average temperature of the working fluid, resulting in lower Isp. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, actually, I noted that you can increase the chamber size <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> as long as you can effectively couple the core to the working fluid. </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  In other words, the ideal size for the chamber is one which will cast the walls of the chamber into at least partial &quot;shade&quot; from the core, but only barely.  Details of the exact size and shape will have to be worked out, of course.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
Are the micropores in the walls of the reaction chamber or the quartz bubble itself, it isn't clear in the post? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh, sorry.  The pores are in almost EVERY surface of the thruster which has to interact with hot gas.  So, the outside of the silica lightbulb, the inside of the reaction chamber, and the inside surface of the nozzle if a conventional nozzle is used, or the outside of a plug nozzle.  <br>
<br>
This gas blanket serves two functions: <br>
<br>
First, at the energy density of the Liberty Ship thruster the hydrogen reaction mass is ionized, or all the electrons are stripped off it.  So, in a sense, we have a plasma of proton and electron soup.  This stuff will gleefully corrode about anything it touches, so we blow in the layer of gas to keep the walls of the reaction chamber from eroding.<br>
<br>
Second, the temperature of the gas in the reaction chamber is WAY hotter than the boiling point of anything.  (Yes, I mean anything.  A block of tungsten would be gas in seconds in there.)   Naturally, we have to keep the walls of the chamber cool.  As the cooling gas enters the chamber through the pores, it enters at a low temperature, say 0 degrees celsius.  No matter how fast it heats up, there will be a temperature gradient in the gas blanket, ranging from the entry temperature to full exhaust temperature.  It may be only a few molecules thick, but it exists.  That temperature gradient should allow the chamber walls to survive the conditions without too much trouble.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I'll have to look over the thread again to make sure. Get back to you after that. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sure, ask away!  The more you guys hammer away, the better it gets.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Sorry about the links, I keep most of my information in printed form (I find it easier to read long reports that way), so I don't have easy links at hand. Bad habit. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No problem!  I just like having links so I can see what refs folks are using.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Plus, those were some GREAT links!  <br>
<br>
Now, what those links show are two problems that are fairly common.  <br>
<br>
First, they don't seem to have dates, so I have no idea how current they are.  Remember, the only reason the Liberty Ship is possible at all is the super-low absorptions of silica, which has been driven by a totally seperate industry, micro-lithography.  This work has only been done in the last 2 to 3 years:  Any view of the Nuclear Lightbulb before that would naturally be limited to much lower energies.<br>
<br>
Second, they illustrate what I like to call &quot;deep but narrow thinking.&quot;  IE, in a project like the Liberty Ship, bits and pieces from many different fields must be combined, often in weird ways, to make the thing work.  Folks who are super experts in a given field probably do not even know of the existance of solutions to their problems, because those solutions were made in totally different fields.  <br>
<br>
To see those solutions takes a not-too-bright but stubborn lunatic like myself, who is unwilling to take &quot;its impossible&quot; as a valid response before I've chewed a thing half to death, and is willing to look under any rock for stuff that works.<br>
<br>
Basically, we are getting lucky, folks.  It is only in the last few years that this solution has become possible at all.  Yay us!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
