<br>
Ok, I have fixed the core temp of the thruster at 50,000 C, pretty much because thats the figure mentioned in the articles I have seen.  I suspect the temp must be in that range to get the radiant spectrum in the right place for good silica transmissivity, but I do not know for a fact.<br>
<br>
<br>
Given the Isp I am shooting for, the exhaust speed has to be 30,000 meters per second.  Given the thrust levels I want, the mass flow for the ship has to be 1245 kilograms per second.  Given the speed and the mass, the energy required is 560 Gigajoules per second (Gigawatts).<br>
<br>
Using the mass and the energy, I did some rough calculations and came up with a temperature increase for the propellant of 15,510 degrees celsius, so the exhaust temp is about 15,000 celsius.<br>
<br>
